projects.title: Introducing Service-Learning Research to Master’s Level Counseling Students as a Way of Enhancing their Overall Educational Experience
projects.description: Presented at the Mid-Winter Texas Association for Counselor Education and Supervision Conference. This presentation argues that, by infusing service-learning opportunities with faculty research, students gain valuable insight into the process of conducting future studies and often feel more connected to their program. In this presentation, the process of establishing a research based service-learning program was discussed from initializing such a project to the submission of a manuscript. The presenters will also provide preliminary qualitative data of student’s perception of program allegiance along with their personal experience as the result of such research based service-learning programs. Discussion with the audience focused on implications of the research findings for counseling programs.

profile_positions.company: UNT Child and Family Research Clinic
profile_positions.description: As a former graduate student, I spent an average of 15-20 hours providing no-cost counseling to children, adolescents, and adults in the community. During this time, I worked with a low-income community using creative interventions such as sand tray therapy, play therapy, or expressive arts, to help clients deal with a variety of concerns that vary from mild to moderate. I was also responsible for working with the audio-visual technology, administering and scoring assessments, organizing and maintaining paperwork, and providing supervision and guidance to interns in the clinic.
profile_positions.title: Mental Health Counselor

profile_positions.description: For two years, I assisted in the implementation of a quantitative research project that examined the effectiveness of play therapy on academic achievement with over a hundred local elementary school students across four schools in the district.  Duties included maintaining school partnerships, grant writing, writing for the IRB applications, scheduling, training, assessment administration and scoring, and providing play therapy directly to children. In the second year, I became responsible for providing intensive instruction of child-centered play therapy principles and tenants, training for the administration of numerous assessments, and initiating role-play scenarios for new additions to the research team. Along with administrative duties, my other responsibilities also included introducing school district protocol, prompting parent-teacher consultations, and maintaining, shopping for, and maintaining multiple playrooms in the schools. Results and experiences during research and training phases were presented at state and national conferences, including Crimes Against Children Annual Conference, Texas Association for Play Therapy, and Texas Association for Counselor Education and Supervision.
profile_positions.title: Research Assistant, Play Therapy Instructor, Assessment Trainer, and Volunteer Play Therapist

profile_positions.company: the Denton County Juvenile Detention Center
profile_positions.description: As a counseling intern, I was given all of the responsibilities of a full-time Licensed Professional Counselor.  I conducted individual and group therapy daily, provided assessment and case management for individual clients, and engaged in multi-tiered treatment by coordinating with social workers and other professionals outside of the detention center.  We provided simultaneous treatment using a 12-Step approach to addiction and a structured daily program to help incarcerated children develop personal discipline and positive habits and to realize the possible impact of the choices reflected in each child’s personal disciplines and habits. In order to meet the needs of the population, I also gained experience in rape crisis counseling, gang interventions, addictions counseling, new media group therapy, sand tray therapy, grief and bereavement, and Child Protective Services protocol.
